This document is an EDA notebook to explore descriptive and informative figures of the datasets incldued in the emidata package.

Data

We analyse three datasets: ipapers2018_csdata dataset (psy-realted data items) has 129 records, ipapers2018_psydata dataset (cs-related data items) that has 107 records, and ipapers2018 dataset (analysed papers) with 136 records.

The final number of papers to analyse is 104.

Exploratory analysis

Next exploratory tables and figures attempt to figure out whats going on. The initial assumption of the paper is that the field of mental disorders (md) drives the analysis. So we start exploring the variables related to mental disorder, which are:

## [1] "md"      "md_mul"  "md_sub"  "md_id"   "md_desc"

Mental disorders (MDs)

How many distinct MDs are there?

There are 14 distinct MDs (out of 25). About 79.8% % (N=83) are categorised according to DSH-5. About 20.2% % (N=21) are 23-Dual, 24-Multiple or 25-Suicidal behavior disorder/nonsuicidal self-injury.

Variability of MDs over time?

Top3 MDs?

The top3 MD are categorised in the DSH-5, and they all cover about 46.2% (N=48).

Mental disorders and subtypes

Comorbidity in cases 23-Dual and 24-multiple?

Reminder: About 20.2% % (N=21) are 23-Dual, 24-Multiple or 25-Suicidal Behavior Disorder/Nonsuicidal Self-Injury. We look at MDs which are not categorised according to the DSH-5 (id equal to 23 or 24), and check the field md_mul.

A way to visualizing two discrete variables is by using a stacked bar plot

An alternative way is by using a bubble plot.

What subtypes of illnesses are mentioned (in the papers) per each category of mental disorder in DSH-5?

We look at MDs which are categorised according to the DSH-5 (id <> 23 or 24), and check the field md_sub.
